# How did the earthquake impact the Hatayspor team and the general morale in the club?

## Summary
The Hatayspor team, based in Antakya near the epicenter of the devastating earthquake that struck Turkey and Syria, was deeply affected by the disaster <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. The team experienced not only the loss of at least 35,000 people in the earthquake but also faced uncertainty about the whereabouts of their player Christian Atsu, causing a significant impact on the team's morale <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font><font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. The tragedy further extended into the team when backroom staff were found to have lost family members or needed critical medical treatment, adding to the emotional burden on the players <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font>. The Ghana Football Association called for prayers for Atsu, whose safety was confirmed later, providing some relief to the team and his former club, Everton <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>. Despite the disaster, Atsu managed to score a winning goal for Hatayspor in a match against Kasimpasa S.K. before the earthquake struck <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>.

## Claims
| Claim Sentence | Context |
|---|---|
|<font color=#FF3399>[1]</font> At least 35,000 people have died in the earthquakes.<a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/ghanian-footballer-christian-atsu-missing-turkey-earthquakes/" target="_blank">Source</a>| Atsu who previously played for English clubs Chelsea and Newcastle, signed for Hatayspor late last year. The club is based in Antakya, near the epicenter of the 7.8-magnitude earthquake that struck in the early hours of Feb. 6, one of two major earthquakes, along with ensuing aftershocks which devastated southern Turkey and northern Syria. At least 35,000 people have died in the earthquakes. Atsu scored late in injury time to give Hatayspor a 1-0 win over Istanblul-based Kasimpaa S.K.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> The tentacles of the tragedy extended into the rest of the team, as Adekugbe learned people who work in the backroom staff had either lost family members or required critical treatment from a medical infrastructure struggling to cope with the widespread damage.<a href="https://theathletic.com/4192690/2023/02/13/turkey-earthquake-canadian-soccer-players/" target="_blank">Source</a>| The initial earthquake, and subsequent aftershocks, including a 7.5 magnitude event, is the deadliest in the country since 1939. According to the U.S. Geological Survey, only three earthquakes of 6.0 or larger magnitudes have occurred within 250 km of the Feb. 6 epicenter since 1970. The tentacles of the tragedy extended into the rest of the team, as Adekugbe learned people who work in the backroom staff had either lost family members or required critical treatment from a medical infrastructure struggling to cope with the widespread damage. Thats when Adekugbe, again, thought of Hutchinson and wanted to be near him.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[3]</font> Ghanaian soccer player Christian Atsu is still missing, days after two massive earthquakes struck Turkey and Syria.<a href="https://www.okayafrica.com/christian-atsu-turkey-earthquake/" target="_blank">Source</a>| Ghanaian soccer player Christian Atsu is still missing, days after two massive earthquakes struck Turkey and Syria. Volkan Demirel, the manager of Turkish football club Hataysporthe team Atsu plays forconfirmed the news to Reuters on Wednesday.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[4]</font> Atsu was not immediately accounted for amid search and rescue efforts after the earthquake.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/turkey-syria-earthquake-updates-2-7-23-intl/h_9ca3ad1cf355f10eb73fb3492fc191c4" target="_blank">Source</a>| Let's continue to pray for Christian," the Ghana Football Association tweeted Tuesday. AFP reported Tuesday that Atsu who is currently playing for Turkish team Hatayspor had been found in the southern province of Hatay, citing an interview that Ghana's ambassador to Turkey, Francisca Ashietey-Odunton, gave to radio station based in Accra. Atsu was not immediately accounted for amid search and rescue efforts after the earthquake. The player's former club, Premier League side Everton, said it is "relieved" to hear of his rescue.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> At least 20,000 people have died after the two massive earthquakes rocked Turkey and neighboring Syria on Monday.<a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/soccer-star-christian-atsu-remains-missing-turkey-earthquake-rcna69984" target="_blank">Source</a>| Atsu last tweeted after scoring the winning goal in his side's 1-0 victory over Kasmpasa S.K. on Sunday. At least 20,000 people have died after the two massive earthquakes rocked Turkey and neighboring Syria on Monday. The first temblor struck Turkey and neighboring Syria in the early hours, and registered at magnitude-7.8, a "major" earthquake on the official magnitude scale.|
